      <hedline>
        <hl1>Leave Cancer Out of Politics</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Robert Ivker letter, commenting on August 19 article, urges Repr Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton to leave women's health issues, particularly breast cancer, out of campaign for US Senate seat from New York</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>When Senator John McCain was unfairly criticized regarding his support for breast cancer financing during the New York Republican presidential primary, I had hoped it would be an isolated incident of bad taste and dishonesty. Unfortunately, this has proved not to be the case.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>When Senator John McCain was unfairly criticized regarding his support for breast cancer financing during the New York Republican presidential primary, I had hoped it would be an isolated incident of bad taste and dishonesty. Unfortunately, this has proved not to be the case.</p>
        <p>An Aug. 19 news article described the accusations between Representative Rick A. Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton, the New York Senate candidates, on women's health issues, particularly breast cancer. If there is one issue that should be placed outside the political arena, it is cancer. Candidates should state their positions, tout their records and leave the rest to the voters.</p>
        <p>ROBERT IVKER, M.D.  Newark, Aug. 23, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is chairman of the radiation oncology department at Newark Beth Israel Medical Center.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
